[There were 10 new confirmed and 123 new suspected cases in week 49 (6-12 Dec 2021), indicating that Lassa fever (LF) virus transmission is continuing. The graph in Figure 6 indicates that a peak of cases occurred in week 7 last year (10-16 Feb 2020). There were 3 deaths among the confirmed cases for week 49 2021. Unfortunately, there are 2 newly infected health care workers during the current week (week 49).

The report above confirms that, so far this year (2021), Edo, Ondo, and Taraba states have the most confirmed cases. The number of states affected increased to 16, and the number of local government areas (LGAs) with at least one case is 64. Although not mentioned explicitly in the summary above, Baushi State's Primary Healthcare Development Agency, says it has recorded 153 suspected cases of Lassa fever between January and December 2021 (https://guardian.ng/news/bauchi-records-153-lassa-fever-cases-in-1year/).

Nigeria is now in the period of relatively lower case numbers but is likely to increase in coming weeks. The peak is not as high so far this year (2021) as in previous years, as illustrated in the graph in Figure 6. There has been a peak in case numbers between weeks 1 and 11 (Jan-Mar) over the past 4 years and will be the case again for the year 2021 but at a lower level.

Transmission of LF virus occurs when individuals are in contact with rodent reservoir host excreta or are within healthcare facilities. It is encouraging to learn that risk communications and community engagement activities this year (2021) have been scaled up across states using television, radio, print, social media, and other strategies for avoidance of contact with rodent virus reservoirs and their excreta. One hopes that this is why there are fewer cases this year (2021).

Images of the rodent reservoirs of Lassa fever virus:
_Mastomys natalensis_: https://www.inaturalist.org/taxa/45326-Mastomys-natalensis
_Mastomys erythroleucus_ and _Hylomyscus pamfi_: http://punchng.com/nigerias-large-rat-population-threatens-lassa-fever-war/

One hopes that the ongoing public information campaign will help the local population to avoid the entry of these reservoir rodents into their houses and other buildings. - Mod.TY

